{"title_page": "Leevi Aaltonen", "text_new": "{{short description|Finnish ice hockey forward|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2019}}\n{{Infobox ice hockey player\n| name = Leevi Aaltonen\n| image =\n| image_size =\n| caption = \n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|2001|01|24|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Mikkeli]], Finland\n| height_ft = 5\n| height_in = 9\n| weight_lb = 176\n| position = [[Forward (ice hockey)|Forward]]\n| shoots = Left\n| league = [[Liiga]]\n| team = [[KalPa]]\n| prospect_team = \n| prospect_league =\n| former_teams =\n| ntl_team = Finland\n| draft = 130th overall\n| draft_year = 2019\n| draft_team = [[New York Rangers]]\n| career_start = 2019\n| career_end = \n}}\n'''Leevi Aaltonen''' (born January 24, 2001) is a Finnish [[ice hockey]] [[forward (ice hockey)|forward]] who plays for [[KalPa]] in [[Liiga]].  He played in 7 games for KalPa in 2018\u201319 with no goals and one assist.<ref name=elite>{{cite web|title=Leevi Aaltonen|url=https://www.eliteprospects.com/player/347570/leevi-aaltonen|accessdate=2019-06-24|publisher=Elite Prospects}}</ref>  He was drafted by the [[New York Rangers]] in the 5th round of the [[2019 NHL Entry Draft]] with the 130th pick in the draft.<ref>{{cite web|title=Rangers GM Jeff Gorton feels good about his seven other picks in draft|accessdate=2019-06-24|publisher=Newsday|date=June 22, 2019|url=https://www.newsday.com/sports/hockey/rangers/jeff-gorton-kaapo-kakko-matthew-robertson-1.32780757|author=Stephenson, Colin}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{icehockeystats}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Aaltonen, Leevi}}\n[[Category:2001 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Finnish ice hockey forwards]]\n[[Category:Iisalmen Peli-Karhut players]]\n[[Category:KalPa players]]\n[[Category:New York Rangers draft picks]]\n[[Category:People from Mikkeli]]\n\n\n{{Finland-icehockey-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Finnish ice hockey forward|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2019}}\n{{Infobox ice hockey player\n| name = Leevi Aaltonen\n| image =\n| image_size =\n| caption = \n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|2001|01|24|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Mikkeli]], Finland\n| height_ft = 5\n| height_in = 9\n| weight_lb = 176\n| position = [[Forward (ice hockey)|Forward]]\n| shoots = Left\n| league = [[Liiga]]\n| team = [[KalPa]]\n| prospect_team = \n| prospect_league =\n| former_teams =\n| ntl_team = Finland\n| draft = 130th overall\n| draft_year = 2019\n| draft_team = [[New York Rangers]]\n| career_start = 2019\n| career_end = \n}}\n'''Leevi Aaltonen''' (born January 24, 2001) is a Finnish [[ice hockey]] [[forward (ice hockey)|forward]] who plays for [[KalPa]] in [[Liiga]].  He played in 7 games for KalPa in 2018-19 with no goals and one assist.<ref name=elite>{{cite web|title=Leevi Aaltonen|url=https://www.eliteprospects.com/player/347570/leevi-aaltonen|accessdate=2019-06-24|publisher=Elite Prospects}}</ref>  He was drafted by the [[New York Rangers]] in the 5th round of the [[2019 NHL Entry Draft]] with the 130th pick in the draft.<ref>{{cite web|title=Rangers GM Jeff Gorton feels good about his seven other picks in draft|accessdate=2019-06-24|publisher=Newsday|date=June 22, 2019|url=https://www.newsday.com/sports/hockey/rangers/jeff-gorton-kaapo-kakko-matthew-robertson-1.32780757|author=Stephenson, Colin}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{icehockeystats}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Aaltonen, Leevi}}\n[[Category:2001 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Finnish ice hockey forwards]]\n[[Category:Iisalmen Peli-Karhut players]]\n[[Category:KalPa players]]\n[[Category:New York Rangers draft picks]]\n[[Category:People from Mikkeli]]\n\n\n{{Finland-icehockey-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Majavah", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:clean up,typo(s) fixed: 2018-19 \u2192 2018\u201319", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Leevi_Aaltonen"}
{"title_page": "Daniel Bernardi", "text_new": "<!--  Please do not remove or change this AfD message until the discussion has been closed.  -->\n{{no footnotes|date=November 2018}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n| name        = Daniel Bernardi\n| image       =\n| image_size  = \n| alt         = \n| caption     = \n| birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1964|6|16}}\n| birth_place = [[San Juan, Puerto Rico]]\n| spouse      = Helen Na \n| fields      = [[media studies]], [[cultural studies]],<br/> [[narrative theory]], [[critical race theory]]\n| workplaces  = [[San Francisco State University]], [[United States Navy Reserve]]s, El Dorado Films\n| alma_mater  = [[University of Arizona]], [[UCLA]]\n}}\n'''Daniel Leonard Bernardi''' (born June 16, 1964) is a Professor of Cinema at San Francisco State University<ref>[https://cinema.sfsu.edu/people/faculty/daniel-bernardi School of Cinema  at San Francisco State]</ref>, founder and President of [http://www.eldoradofilms.net/ El Dorado Films] and Commander in the U.S. Navy Reserves. Bernardi earned a Bachelor of Arts in Radio-TV (1984) and a Masters of Arts in Media Arts (1988) from the [[University of Arizona]]. He went on to earn a PhD in Film and [[Television Studies]] from [[UCLA]] (1994). He completed a University of California [[postdoctoral research]] fellowship in 1997.\n\nHis main academic interests are [[media studies]], [[narrative theory]], [[critical race theory]], and rumors as narrative IEDS.  His work in media, which is perhaps most well known, emphasizes [[whiteness studies|whiteness]] as a historical formation of meanings. Borrowing from Michael Omi and Howard Winant's theory of racial formation, he argues that whiteness is a historically powerful set of meanings that serves to either implicitly or explicitly dominate the shifting and reforming meaning of race in U.S. media.\n\nBernardi is also a documentary filmmaker<ref>[http://www.eldoradofilms.net/filmmakers/daniel-l-bernardi/ El Dorado Films]</ref>. His current body of work focuses on telling the veteran story. One of his more recent films, [https://www.imdb.com/title/tt8075286/ The American War] (2018), tells the story of the Vietnam War from the perspective of the Vietcong. Another used discovered archival footage to tell the story of first World War, and is titled [https://www.imdb.com/title/tt9441390/?ref_=rvi_tt The War to End all Wars]. Both films are distributed by [https://www.journeyman.tv/about/about-us Journeyman Pictures].\n\n==Career==\nBernardi has taught film, television and [[new media]] at [[UC Riverside]] (1997\u20131998), [[UCLA]] (1999-2000), Arizona State University (1999-2011), and [[San Francisco State University|SFSU]] (2011\u2013Present). He was awarded a [[Ford Foundation]] Dissertation Fellowship (1994), a UC President's Post-Doctoral Fellowship (1995\u20131997), and a [[Fulbright Fellowship]] (2009).  His deployment to Iraq prevented his acceptance of the Fulbright Fellowship.  From 1998 to 2000, he worked for the [[Sci-Fi Channel]] as a consultant, writer and producer/host of the web feature ''Future Now'' (since deleted).\n\nDaniel Bernardi has earned a reputation of notoriety among the more avid Star Trek fans due to his writings about the role of race in the films.<ref>Los Angeles Times, [https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-1995-03-15-mn-42986-story.html Trekking Through College]</ref>\n\nBernardi is also an officer in the [[United States Navy Reserve]]s.  He has served at sea on the {{USS|Coronado|AGF-11|6}}, the {{USS|John C. Stennis|CVN-74}}, the {{USS|Blue Ridge|LCC-19}}, and the {{USS|Cleveland|LPD-7}}, as well as at shore in Italy, Indonesia, Japan, Korea, Vietnam and at the Pentagon with the Chief of Navy Information.  From May 2009 to February 2010 he was recalled to Active Duty in support of Operation Iraqi Freedom for ten months.  In Iraq, Bernardi served with US Special Forces as the Public Affairs Officer for [[Iraqi Special Operations Forces|Special Operations Task Force-Central]], where he trained [[Iraqi Special Operations Forces]] (ISOF) and Emergency Response Brigade (ERB) Soldiers on combat camera and media operations.  He also managed US media embeds, including CNN, NBC and AP, and US Army and US Navy journalists and photographers.  In 2011 he returned to Active Duty for nine months and served as the Mission Public Affairs Officer for [[Pacific Partnership|Pacific Partnership 2011]], an annual humanitarian assistance initiative sponsored by the [[United States Pacific Fleet|U.S. Pacific Fleet]].  Bernardi managed a team of military (U.S., Australian and New Zealand) and NGO (Project Hope) photographers, videographers and writers assigned to document and report on the mission.\n\nFollowing his tour in Iraq and the South Pacific, Bernardi, working with a larger research team including [[H. L. (Bud) Goodall Jr.]], received a $1.6 million renewable grant from the Office of Naval Research to catalogue and study the impact rumors have on counterinsurgency operations. As an example, when multinational forces began a cattle vaccination program in 2005, a rumor spread among the Iraqis that U.S. forcers were poisoning their livestock. Though they had intended on using modern medicine to protect their food supplies, the rumor completely disarmed their efforts. In order to combat such debilitating narratives, Bernardi and his team worked to create a comprehensive database of known Islamist narratives and reveal how these narratives are used to influence populations in the Middle East and North Africa. The hope is that expeditionary forces would have access to these narratives and, through the team's analysis' on hand, work against them.\n\nIn 2012, Bernardi launched the Veteran Documentary Corps <ref>[https://lca.sfsu.edu/centers/vdc College of liberal and Creative  Arts]</ref> (VDC) project. Founded by donations and grants, the VA and National Cemetery Administration including, VDC produces and exhibits short documentaries on the struggles and successes of veterans from across the world.  To-date, VDC has produced and distributed fifty short documentaries <ref>[https://www.imdb.com/search/title/?companies=co0022187 El Dorado Films IMDB]</ref> on veterans dealing with [[posttraumatic stress disorder]] (PTSD), the fall-out of the former \"[[don't ask, don't tell]]\" policy, and a range of other topics.  The films are made by professional filmmakers.  Bernardi acts as executive producer.  He has also directed two of the films, one on [http://www.aspiriant.com/tim-kochis/ Tim Koches] (Vietnam War) and one on Michael Blackwell (Iraq War).  Blackwell was a [[Combat Camera]] photographer that served with Bernardi in the U.S. Iraq War. Bernardi directed many of the films, including the award-winning Noble Sissle\u2019s Syncopated Regime (2019).  Many of the films in the series are directed by professional filmmakers, including [[Jesse Moss (filmmaker)|Jesse Moss]], Andr\u00e9s Gallegos, Sylvia Turchin, Eliciana Nascimento, among others <ref>[http://www.eldoradofilms.net/filmmakers/ El Dorado Films Filmmakers]</ref>.\n\nThe Veteran Documentary Corps was met with wide acclaim, and was received positively from veterans and the public alike. Created in 2018 by Bernardi, El Dorado Films brought superior talent and organization to the Veteran Documentary Corps' mission of creating 100 'shorts' by 2020.\n\n==Bibliography==\n\n===As author===\n* [https://www.ucpress.edu/blog/29639/off-the-page-screenwriting-in-the-era-of-media-convergence-available-now-for-courses/ Off the Page:  Screenwriting in the Era of Media Convergence (co-author)].  2017.  University of California Press.\n\nExamines the business and craft of screenwriting in the era of media convergence. Daniel Bernardi and Julian Hoxter use the recent history of screenwriting labor coupled with close analysis of scripts in the context of the screenwriting paraindustry\u2014from \u201chow to write a winning script\u201d books to screenwriting software\u2014to explore the state of screenwriting today. They address the conglomerate studios making tentpole movies, expanded television, Indiewood, independent animation, microbudget scripting, the video games industry, and online content creation. Designed for students, producers, and writers who want to understand what studios want and why they want it, this book also examines how scripting is developing in the convergent media, beneath and beyond the Hollywood tentpole. By addressing specific genres across a wide range of media, this essential volume sets the standard for anyone in the expanded screenwriting industry and the scholars that study it.<ref>[https://www.ucpress.edu/blog/29639/off-the-page-screenwriting-in-the-era-of-media-convergence-available-now-for-courses/ University of California Press Blog]</ref>\n\n* [https://www.amazon.com/Narrative-Landmines-Extremism-Directions-International/dp/0813552516/ref=sr_1_1?s=books&ie=UTF8&qid=1504021833&sr=1-1&keywords=narrative+landmines''Narrative Landmines: Rumors, Islamist Extremism, and the Struggle for Strategic Influence Rumors''] (co-authored).  2012. Rutgers University Press.\n\nBernardi and his co-authors characterize rumors as bits and pieces of prevailing narrative systems and local cultural artifacts, and that their anonymous origin and dubious truth claims afford them a type of concealment until their effects are known and the damage is done.  Focusing on the impact of rumors on counterinsurgency operations (Iraq), counter terrorism whisper campaigns (Indonesia), and civil disobedience online (Singapore), they argue that rumors are ''[[narrative IEDs]]'', or Improvised Explosive Device, in that they\u2019re constructed of locally available materials and hidden in the landscape until detonation.  Bernardi and his co-authors see rumors as similarly ''ad hoc'', constructed of bits and pieces of narrative systems, and lying unseen to the military information operator, diplomat, civic outreach coordinator, or business strategist until exploding and disrupting expensive and highly wrought communication campaigns<ref>[https://www.rutgersuniversitypress.org/narrative-landmines/9780813552514 Rutgers University Press]</ref>.\n\n*''[https://www.barnesandnoble.com/w/star-trek-and-history-daniel-leonard-bernardi/1111883392 Star Trek and History:  Race-ing Toward a White Future\". 1998. Rutgers University Press]. {{ISBN|0-8135-2466-0}}\n\nBernardi traces the shifting and reforming meaning of race articulated throughout the ''[[Star Trek]]'' television series, feature films, and fan community, investigating and, in his word, \"politicizing\" the presentation of race in ''Star Trek'' in the original series of the 1960s, the feature films and television spin-offs of the 1980s and 1990s, and the current fan community on the Internet. Through both critical and historical analysis, he proposes a method of studying the framing of race in popular film and television that integrates [[sociology]], [[critical theory]] and [[cultural studies]]. Bernardi goes on to examine the representational and narrative functions of [[race (classification of human beings)|race]] in ''Star Trek'' and explores how the meaning of \"race\" in the science fiction series has been facilitated or constrained by creative and network decision-making, by genre, by [[intertextuality]], and by fans. He interprets how the changing social and political movements of the times have influenced the production and meaning of \"Trek\" texts and the ways in which the ongoing series negotiated and reflected these turbulent histories.  Unpopular with many [[Trekker (Star Trek)|Trekker]]s, ''Star Trek and History'' went into a second printing after a year of its original publication.  Other readers feel Bernardi apologies for Star Trek's racial vision.<ref>[https://www.rutgersuniversitypress.org/star-trek-and-history/9780813524665 Rutgers University Press]</ref>\n\n===As editor===\n* [https://www.amazon.com/Race-American-Film-volumes-Visions/dp/0313398399 Race in American Film: Voices and Visions That Shaped a Nation, Volumes I, II and III]. (co-editor). 2017. Greenwood Publishers. {{ISBN|978-0313398391}}\n*[http://wsupress.wayne.edu/books/detail/hollywoods-chosen-people ''Hollywood's Chosen People: The Jewish Experience in American Cinema''](co-edited). 2012. Wayne State University Press.  {{ISBN|9780814334829}}\n*[http://www.utexas.edu/utpress/books/berfil.html ''Filming Difference: Actors, Directors, Producers and Writers on Gender, Race and Sexuality in Film.''] 2009.  University of Texas Press.  {{ISBN|0-292-71974-4}}\n*[http://www.routledge.com/books/details/9780415774130/ ''The Persistence of Whiteness.'']  2007.  Routledge.  {{ISBN|0-415-77412-8}}\n*[http://www.upress.umn.edu/book-division/books/classic-hollywood-classic-whiteness ''Classic Hollywood/Classic Whiteness.'']  2001.  University of Minnesota Press.  {{ISBN|0-8166-3239-1}}\n*''[https://www.amazon.com/Birth-Whiteness-Emergence-United-States/dp/0813522765 The Birth of Whiteness:  Race and the Emergence of U.S. Cinema].''  1996.  Rutgers University Press.  {{ISBN|0-8135-2276-5}}\n\nIn these books, Bernardi relies on a range of scholars to show how race in general and whiteness in particular formed unique representational, narrational, and institutional patterns across U.S. film history.  The introductions to each book set out a broad theory of whiteness in American film that, in brief, positions whiteness as a performance about who passes and who doesn't pass as white \u2014 and what it means in specific films and periods of film history to either pass or not pass as white.  The last book in the series, ''Filming Difference'', includes essays and interviews by filmmakers who address critically and creatively how they go about representing race, gender and sexuality in their work.  <!-- Comment moved to Discussion page -->.\n\n===As filmmaker===\n* [https://www.youtube.com/playlist?list=PLywVcCl5U2n_7XRlxqZZmcewE4iu_LRLx VALOR Film Series]: Stories that honor our country's heroes and their accomplishments.\n*[https://www.youtube.com/playlist?list=PLywVcCl5U2n-j4vU0dIVoN43CITKWbIsh Legacy Films] (Made in partnership with the National Cemetery Administration): A series of short films on veterans buried in San Francisco and Golden Gate National Cemeteries\u2013 from stories of service in Civil War to Buffalo Soldier, from WWI to Vietnam to Iraq. \n* [https://www.imdb.com/title/tt9377262/?ref_=nv_sr_1 Noble Sissle's Syncopated Ragtime]: In this Academy Awards eligible documentary, Noble Sissle's incredible life spans \"The Harlem Hellfighters\" of World War I, Broadway Theatre, the Civil Rights movement, and decades of Black cultural production in this short, award-winning documentary.\n* [https://www.imdb.com/title/tt8777138/?ref_=nm_knf_t1 Guy Hircefeld, A Guy with a Camera]: In this Academy Awards eligible documentary, Guy Hircefeld, a veteran that served in the Israeli military at the start of its occupation of Palestine in the 1980s, now fights against Israeli occupation, ethnic cleansing, and environmental warfare. His only weapon is a camera.\n*  [https://www.imdb.com/title/tt9422390/?ref_=ttpl_pl_tt Nurse Helen Fairchild]: Bravery, Compassion and the will to save lives motivated the young Nurse Helen Fairchild to leave home in Pennsylvania and embark on a journey to Europe, where she served as a surgical nurse during the World War I.\n* [https://www.imdb.com/title/tt11540678/ Frank Maselskis: from WWII POW to Chosin Reservoir Survivor]: A prisoner of war in World War II, Frank Maselskis decides to join the Korean War, where he participates in the battle of Chosin, a brutal combat that took place in the most extreme weather conditions.\n* [https://www.imdb.com/title/tt11540612/ Alene B. Duerk: The First Woman Admiral]: Alene B. Duerk: The First Woman Admiral is a short documentary that tells the story of how Alene Duerk overcame gender stereotypes in the military to accomplish the highest rank ever achieved by a woman in the history of the US Navy.\n\n===As producer===\n* [http://www.eldoradofilms.net/profiles/ Women in Science]: Iliana Nossa (The Ionosphere) & Anne Virkki (Near Earth Asteroids), two female scientists at Arecibo Observatory, Puerto Rico.\n* [https://www.instagram.com/eldoradofilms_/ Cemetery Profiles and Field Notes]: In this series, we hope to tell the story of our National Cemeteries. Veteran Documentary Corps shot these films in late April 2019 as part of our partnership with the National Cemetery Administration. All films are available on our social media platforms.\n*[https://www.imdb.com/title/tt8231488/ Madame Mars] is an award-winning short film about women in space. As a new space age dawns, have women come far enough to go farther than they ever have before? Women have faced challenges while trying to study and explore Mars\u2013 from early space age pioneers to those currently working.\n*[https://objectorfilm.com/ Objector] directed by Molly Stuart tells the story of Atalya Ben Abba. Like all Israeli teenagers, Atalya Ben Abba is obligated to become a soldier. Unlike most, she questions the ethics of her country\u2019s military and becomes determined to challenge this rite of passage. Objector follows Atalya through her conscientious objection, imprisonment, and beyond, as she attempts to reconcile her Jewish identity, her love for her family and her homeland, and her dedication to Palestinian rights\n\n==Selected publications==\n*Bernardi, Daniel. ''The Birth of Whiteness:  Race and the Emergence of U.S. Cinema.''  1996.  Rutgers University Press.  {{ISBN|0-8135-2276-5}}\n*Bernardi, Daniel. ''Star Trek and History:  Race-ing Toward a White Future''.  1998. Rutgers University Press. {{ISBN|0-8135-2466-0}}\n*Bernardi, Daniel.  [http://flowtv.org/2005/04/cyborg-donna-haraway-race-pornography-hate-speech/ \"Where's the Beef?\"] ''Flow On-line'', Volume 2.  April 1, 2005.\n*[http://smallwarsjournal.com/jrnl/art/narrative-landmines \"Narrative Landmines: The Explosive Effects of Rumors in Syria and Insurgencies Around the World\"].  ''Small Wars Journal''.  March 21, 2013.\n* Word:ChristChurch, Autumn Season 2017. \"[https://www.audiomack.com/song/word-christchurch/james-gleick-time-travel James Gleick: Time Travel Feat. James Gleick, Dr Daniel Bernardi (interviewer)]\".  Audiomack.  July 19, 2017.\n*[http://startrekdom.blogspot.com/2007/06/prof-daniel-bernardi-on-star-trek-and.html \"Prof. Daniel Bernardi on Star Trek and Race.\"] (interview with Bernardi) ''Trekdom - Star Trek Fanzine''. June 25, 2007.\n*[http://www.federalnewsradio.com/1167/3539852/In-Depth-Show-Blog---January-10-2014 \"Lt. Cmdr. Daniel Bernardi.\"  ''In Depth Show''].  Federal News Radio.  January 10, 2014. Radio.\n\n==Sources quoting Bernardi==\n*[http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2011/09/08/scitech/main20103413.shtml \"Beam Me Up, Scotty\": 45 Years of Star Trek]. CBS News Tech Online.  September 8, 2011.\n*Di Rado, Alicia. \"[http://articles.latimes.com/1995-02-20/local/me-34149_1_star-trek Boldly Going to College: Fans of `Star Trek' TV series and movies have the chance to debate meaning and metaphor of cult hit's characters in campus clubs-and in the classroom].\"  ''Los Angeles Times''.  Feb 20, 1995.\n*Hayward, Susan.  ''Cinema Studies: The Key Concepts''.  Second Edition.  200. Routledge.\n*Johnson, Chloe.  [http://www.goldengatexpress.org/2014/10/13/fleet-week-2014/ \"Civilians Get A Taste of Naval Life At Annual Fleet Week\"].  ''Golden Gate XPress''. October 13, 2014.\n*Neary, Lynn.  ''[https://www.npr.org/programs/specials/racism/hollywood/010906.hollywood.html Racism on the Silver Screen]''. National Public Radio.  September 6, 2001.\n*Ramos, Jonathon.  [http://www.sfweekly.com/exhibitionist/2014/08/04/san-francisco-state-university-named-top-25-film-school \"San Francisco State University Among Top 25 Film Schools.\"]  SF Weekly.  August 4, 2014.\n*Ramsey, Campbell. [http://articles.orlandosentinel.com/2005-06-14/news/lchapman14.090_1_tom-chapman-mascotte-alabama Working in the background:  Tom Chapman rings down the curtain on 55 years in Movies, TV, and on Broadway in roles as an 'extra.]  ''Orlando Sentinel''. June 14, 2005.\n*Rico, Jack.  [https://www.nbcnews.com/news/latino/latino-directors-movies-may-nab-major-oscars-once-again-no-n852356 \"Latino Directors, Movies May Nab Major Oscars, But Once Again, No Actors\"].  ''NBC News''.  March 3, 2018.\n*Gordon, Dan. [http://newsroom.ucla.edu/stories/970829TrekkieAuthor \"Trekkie Author Explores Race Issue\"].  ''UCLA Today''. August 29, 1997.\n*Di Rado, Alicia. [https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-1995-03-15-mn-42986-story.html \"Trekking Through College: Classes Explore Modern Society Using the World of 'Star Trek'\"]  ''Los Angeles Times''.  March 15, 1995.\n*Smith, Vincent.  [https://pittnews.com/article/8933/archives/a-tale-of-two-monsters-how-societal-anxiety-influences-horror/ \"A Tale of Two Monsters: How Societal Anxiety Influences Horror\"].  ''The Pitt News''. October 30, 2013.\n*Walker, Dave. \"Hope for a better, prejudice-free future was the appeal of 'Star Trek'\" '' The Times-Picayune''.  May 10, 2009.\n*Wester, Shanna. [https://www.statepress.com/article/2010/11/does-asu-have-a-porn-problem/ \"Does ASU have a Porn Problem?\"].  ''The State Press''. November 12, 2010.\n\n*Foremski, Tom. [http://www.zdnet.com/blog/foremski/us-military-seeks-to-defuse-stories-used-as-weapons/1999 ''US military seeks to \"defuse stories used as weapons\"'']. [https://www.zdnet.com/ ZD Net]. 10/14/11\n*Miles, Donna. [https://web.archive.org/web/20140106212340/http://www.defense.gov/news/newsarticle.aspx?id=121434 \"Reservist Leads Project to Connect American Public, Veterans\"].  ''American Forces Press Service''.  [https://www.defense.gov/ US Department of Defense]. January 6, 2014.\n*Morales, Jonathan.  [http://news.sfsu.edu/documentaries-convey-veterans-experiences \"Documentaries convey veterans' experiences\"]. ''[https://news.sfsu.edu/ SF State News]'' (University Communications).  October, 2013.\n*Newitz, Annalee. \"[https://www.jstor.org/stable/41689233 Whites on Film]\"  ''Cineaste'', Vol. 25, No. 2 (2000): 46-48. [https://www.jstor.org/?refreqid=excelsior%3A5cdc2686519a688e26995a5529148104 Jstor]. (Review of Bernardi's edited volume ''The Birth of Whiteness''.)\n*Philip, Mathhew. [http://www.stuff.co.nz/entertainment/film/92412857/making-sense-of-movies-and-the-world \"Making sense of movies and the world.\"]  Stuff. [https://www.stuff.co.nz/ Stuff]. May 13, 2017.\n*\"[https://web.archive.org/web/20120205215417/http://www.sfsu.edu/~sfsumag/archive/fall_11/rumor.html Rumor Threat]\".  [https://magazine.sfsu.edu/ SF State Magazine Online].  Fall, 2011.\n*Russell, Michael.  [http://www.dvidshub.net/news/73582/university-arizona-graduate-participates-humanitarian-mission \"University of Arizona Graduate Participates in Humanitarian Mission.\"]  [https://www.dvidshub.net/ Defense Video & Imagery Distribution System (DVIDS)].  July 12, 2011.\n*Swartz, Angela.  [https://web.archive.org/web/20160304064912/http://www.smdailyjournal.com/articles/lnews/2013-11-09/new-website-tells-war-vets-stories-san-mateo-resident-and-iraq-war-veteran-participants-in-project/1776425113073.html \"New Website Tells War Vets' Stories: San Mateo Resident and Iraq War Veteran Participants in Project\"].  ''[https://www.dailyjournal.com/ The Daily Journal]''.  November 9, 2013.\n*Tantibanchachai, Chanapa and Hughes, Carol. [http://asunews.asu.edu/20110215_nationalsecurity \"ASU research helps impact in US anti-terrorist program.\"]  [https://asunow.asu.edu/ ASU News] - Online.  February 15, 2011.\n*[http://www.sfsu.edu/~news/2011/fall/15.html ''New cinema chair studies \"narrative IEDs\"'']. [https://news.sfsu.edu/ SF State News]. 09/29/11\n*Ruth La Ferla, [https://www.nytimes.com/2019/10/29/style/its-halloween-heres-what-is-haunting-the-runways-alien-chic.html?rref=collection/sectioncollection/arts \"It\u2019s Halloween. Here\u2019s What\u2019s Haunting the Runways\"]. [https://www.nytimes.com/ New York Times]. October 29, 2019\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bernardi, Daniel}}\n[[Category:Film theorists]]\n[[Category:American media scholars]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1964 births]]\n[[Category:People from San Juan, Puerto Rico]]\n[[Category:Arizona State University faculty]]\n[[Category:UCLA Film School alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Arizona alumni]]\n", "text_old": "<!--  Please do not remove or change this AfD message until the discussion has been closed.  -->\n{{no footnotes|date=November 2018}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n| name        = Daniel Bernardi\n| image       =\n| image_size  = \n| alt         = \n| caption     = \n| birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1964|6|16}}\n| birth_place = [[San Juan, Puerto Rico]]\n| spouse      = Helen Na \n| fields      = [[media studies]], [[cultural studies]],<br/> [[narrative theory]], [[critical race theory]]\n| workplaces  = [[San Francisco State University]], [[United States Navy Reserve]]s, El Dorado Films\n| alma_mater  = [[University of Arizona]], [[UCLA]]\n}}\n'''Daniel Leonard Bernardi''' (born June 16, 1964) is a Professor of Cinema at San Francisco State University<ref>[https://cinema.sfsu.edu/people/faculty/daniel-bernardi School of Cinema  at San Francisco State]</ref>, founder and President of [http://www.eldoradofilms.net/ El Dorado Films] and Commander in the U.S. Navy Reserves. Bernardi earned a Bachelor of Arts in Radio-TV (1984) and a Masters of Arts in Media Arts (1988) from the [[University of Arizona]]. He went on to earn a PhD in Film and [[Television Studies]] from [[UCLA]] (1994). He completed a University of California [[postdoctoral research]] fellowship in 1997.\n\nHis main academic interests are [[media studies]], [[narrative theory]], [[critical race theory]], and rumors as narrative IEDS.  His work in media, which is perhaps most well known, emphasizes [[whiteness studies|whiteness]] as a historical formation of meanings. Borrowing from Michael Omi and Howard Winant's theory of racial formation, he argues that whiteness is a historically powerful set of meanings that serves to either implicitly or explicitly dominate the shifting and reforming meaning of race in U.S. media.\n\nBernardi is also a documentary filmmaker<ref>[http://www.eldoradofilms.net/filmmakers/daniel-l-bernardi/ El Dorado Films]</ref>. His current body of work focuses on telling the veteran story. One of his more recent films, [https://www.imdb.com/title/tt8075286/ The American War] (2018), tells the story of the Vietnam War from the perspective of the Vietcong. Another used discovered archival footage to tell the story of first World War, and is titled [https://www.imdb.com/title/tt9441390/?ref_=rvi_tt The War to End all Wars]. Both films are distributed by [https://www.journeyman.tv/about/about-us Journeyman Pictures].\n\n==Career==\nBernardi has taught film, television and [[new media]] at [[UC Riverside]] (1997\u20131998), [[UCLA]] (1999-2000), Arizona State University (1999-2011), and [[San Francisco State University|SFSU]] (2011\u2013Present). He was awarded a [[Ford Foundation]] Dissertation Fellowship (1994), a UC President's Post-Doctoral Fellowship (1995\u20131997), and a [[Fulbright Fellowship]] (2009).  His deployment to Iraq prevented his acceptance of the Fulbright Fellowship.  From 1998 to 2000, he worked for the [[Sci-Fi Channel]] as a consultant, writer and producer/host of the web feature ''Future Now'' (since deleted).\n\nDaniel Bernardi has earned a reputation of notoriety among the more avid Star Trek fans due to his writings about the role of race in the films.<ref>Los Angeles Times, [https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-1995-03-15-mn-42986-story.html Trekking Through College]</ref>\n\nBernardi is also an officer in the [[United States Navy Reserve]]s.  He has served at sea on the {{USS|Coronado|AGF-11|6}}, the {{USS|John C. Stennis|CVN-74}}, the {{USS|Blue Ridge|LCC-19}}, and the {{USS|Cleveland|LPD-7}}, as well as at shore in Italy, Indonesia, Japan, Korea, Vietnam and at the Pentagon with the Chief of Navy Information.  From May 2009 to February 2010 he was recalled to Active Duty in support of Operation Iraqi Freedom for ten months.  In Iraq, Bernardi served with US Special Forces as the Public Affairs Officer for [[Iraqi Special Operations Forces|Special Operations Task Force-Central]], where he trained [[Iraqi Special Operations Forces]] (ISOF) and Emergency Response Brigade (ERB) Soldiers on combat camera and media operations.  He also managed US media embeds, including CNN, NBC and AP, and US Army and US Navy journalists and photographers.  In 2011 he returned to Active Duty for nine months and served as the Mission Public Affairs Officer for [[Pacific Partnership|Pacific Partnership 2011]], an annual humanitarian assistance initiative sponsored by the [[United States Pacific Fleet|U.S. Pacific Fleet]].  Bernardi managed a team of military (U.S., Australian and New Zealand) and NGO (Project Hope) photographers, videographers and writers assigned to document and report on the mission.\n\nFollowing his tour in Iraq and the South Pacific, Bernardi, working with a larger research team including [[H. L. (Bud) Goodall Jr.]], received a $1.6 million renewable grant from the Office of Naval Research to catalogue and study the impact rumors have on counterinsurgency operations. As an example, when multinational forces began a cattle vaccination program in 2005, a rumor spread among the Iraqis that U.S. forcers were poisoning their livestock. Though they had intended on using modern medicine to protect their food supplies, the rumor completely disarmed their efforts. In order to combat such debilitating narratives, Bernardi and his team worked to create a comprehensive database of known Islamist narratives and reveal how these narratives are used to influence populations in the Middle East and North Africa. The hope is that expeditionary forces would have access to these narratives and, through the team's analysis' on hand, work against them.\n\nIn 2012, Bernardi launched the Veteran Documentary Corps <ref>[https://lca.sfsu.edu/centers/vdc College of liberal and Creative  Arts]</ref> (VDC) project. Founded by donations and grants, the VA and National Cemetery Administration including, VDC produces and exhibits short documentaries on the struggles and successes of veterans from across the world.  To-date, VDC has produced and distributed fifty short documentaries <ref>[https://www.imdb.com/search/title/?companies=co0022187 El Dorado Films IMDB]</ref> on veterans dealing with [[posttraumatic stress disorder]] (PTSD), the fall-out of the former \"[[don't ask, don't tell]]\" policy, and a range of other topics.  The films are made by professional filmmakers.  Bernardi acts as executive producer.  He has also directed two of the films, one on [http://www.aspiriant.com/tim-kochis/ Tim Koches] (Vietnam War) and one on Michael Blackwell (Iraq War).  Blackwell was a [[Combat Camera]] photographer that served with Bernardi in the U.S. Iraq War. Bernardi directed many of the films, including the award-winning Noble Sissle\u2019s Syncopated Regime (2019).  Many of the films in the series are directed by professional filmmakers, including [[Jesse Moss]], Andr\u00e9s Gallegos, Sylvia Turchin, Eliciana Nascimento, among others <ref>[http://www.eldoradofilms.net/filmmakers/ El Dorado Films Filmmakers]</ref>.\n\nThe Veteran Documentary Corps was met with wide acclaim, and was received positively from veterans and the public alike. Created in 2018 by Bernardi, El Dorado Films brought superior talent and organization to the Veteran Documentary Corps' mission of creating 100 'shorts' by 2020.\n\n==Bibliography==\n\n===As author===\n* [https://www.ucpress.edu/blog/29639/off-the-page-screenwriting-in-the-era-of-media-convergence-available-now-for-courses/ Off the Page:  Screenwriting in the Era of Media Convergence (co-author)].  2017.  University of California Press.\n\nExamines the business and craft of screenwriting in the era of media convergence. Daniel Bernardi and Julian Hoxter use the recent history of screenwriting labor coupled with close analysis of scripts in the context of the screenwriting paraindustry\u2014from \u201chow to write a winning script\u201d books to screenwriting software\u2014to explore the state of screenwriting today. They address the conglomerate studios making tentpole movies, expanded television, Indiewood, independent animation, microbudget scripting, the video games industry, and online content creation. Designed for students, producers, and writers who want to understand what studios want and why they want it, this book also examines how scripting is developing in the convergent media, beneath and beyond the Hollywood tentpole. By addressing specific genres across a wide range of media, this essential volume sets the standard for anyone in the expanded screenwriting industry and the scholars that study it.<ref>[https://www.ucpress.edu/blog/29639/off-the-page-screenwriting-in-the-era-of-media-convergence-available-now-for-courses/ University of California Press Blog]</ref>\n\n* [https://www.amazon.com/Narrative-Landmines-Extremism-Directions-International/dp/0813552516/ref=sr_1_1?s=books&ie=UTF8&qid=1504021833&sr=1-1&keywords=narrative+landmines''Narrative Landmines: Rumors, Islamist Extremism, and the Struggle for Strategic Influence Rumors''] (co-authored).  2012. Rutgers University Press.\n\nBernardi and his co-authors characterize rumors as bits and pieces of prevailing narrative systems and local cultural artifacts, and that their anonymous origin and dubious truth claims afford them a type of concealment until their effects are known and the damage is done.  Focusing on the impact of rumors on counterinsurgency operations (Iraq), counter terrorism whisper campaigns (Indonesia), and civil disobedience online (Singapore), they argue that rumors are ''[[narrative IEDs]]'', or Improvised Explosive Device, in that they\u2019re constructed of locally available materials and hidden in the landscape until detonation.  Bernardi and his co-authors see rumors as similarly ''ad hoc'', constructed of bits and pieces of narrative systems, and lying unseen to the military information operator, diplomat, civic outreach coordinator, or business strategist until exploding and disrupting expensive and highly wrought communication campaigns<ref>[https://www.rutgersuniversitypress.org/narrative-landmines/9780813552514 Rutgers University Press]</ref>.\n\n*''[https://www.barnesandnoble.com/w/star-trek-and-history-daniel-leonard-bernardi/1111883392 Star Trek and History:  Race-ing Toward a White Future\". 1998. Rutgers University Press]. {{ISBN|0-8135-2466-0}}\n\nBernardi traces the shifting and reforming meaning of race articulated throughout the ''[[Star Trek]]'' television series, feature films, and fan community, investigating and, in his word, \"politicizing\" the presentation of race in ''Star Trek'' in the original series of the 1960s, the feature films and television spin-offs of the 1980s and 1990s, and the current fan community on the Internet. Through both critical and historical analysis, he proposes a method of studying the framing of race in popular film and television that integrates [[sociology]], [[critical theory]] and [[cultural studies]]. Bernardi goes on to examine the representational and narrative functions of [[race (classification of human beings)|race]] in ''Star Trek'' and explores how the meaning of \"race\" in the science fiction series has been facilitated or constrained by creative and network decision-making, by genre, by [[intertextuality]], and by fans. He interprets how the changing social and political movements of the times have influenced the production and meaning of \"Trek\" texts and the ways in which the ongoing series negotiated and reflected these turbulent histories.  Unpopular with many [[Trekker (Star Trek)|Trekker]]s, ''Star Trek and History'' went into a second printing after a year of its original publication.  Other readers feel Bernardi apologies for Star Trek's racial vision.<ref>[https://www.rutgersuniversitypress.org/star-trek-and-history/9780813524665 Rutgers University Press]</ref>\n\n===As editor===\n* [https://www.amazon.com/Race-American-Film-volumes-Visions/dp/0313398399 Race in American Film: Voices and Visions That Shaped a Nation, Volumes I, II and III]. (co-editor). 2017. Greenwood Publishers. {{ISBN|978-0313398391}}\n*[http://wsupress.wayne.edu/books/detail/hollywoods-chosen-people ''Hollywood's Chosen People: The Jewish Experience in American Cinema''](co-edited). 2012. Wayne State University Press.  {{ISBN|9780814334829}}\n*[http://www.utexas.edu/utpress/books/berfil.html ''Filming Difference: Actors, Directors, Producers and Writers on Gender, Race and Sexuality in Film.''] 2009.  University of Texas Press.  {{ISBN|0-292-71974-4}}\n*[http://www.routledge.com/books/details/9780415774130/ ''The Persistence of Whiteness.'']  2007.  Routledge.  {{ISBN|0-415-77412-8}}\n*[http://www.upress.umn.edu/book-division/books/classic-hollywood-classic-whiteness ''Classic Hollywood/Classic Whiteness.'']  2001.  University of Minnesota Press.  {{ISBN|0-8166-3239-1}}\n*''[https://www.amazon.com/Birth-Whiteness-Emergence-United-States/dp/0813522765 The Birth of Whiteness:  Race and the Emergence of U.S. Cinema].''  1996.  Rutgers University Press.  {{ISBN|0-8135-2276-5}}\n\nIn these books, Bernardi relies on a range of scholars to show how race in general and whiteness in particular formed unique representational, narrational, and institutional patterns across U.S. film history.  The introductions to each book set out a broad theory of whiteness in American film that, in brief, positions whiteness as a performance about who passes and who doesn't pass as white \u2014 and what it means in specific films and periods of film history to either pass or not pass as white.  The last book in the series, ''Filming Difference'', includes essays and interviews by filmmakers who address critically and creatively how they go about representing race, gender and sexuality in their work.  <!-- Comment moved to Discussion page -->.\n\n===As filmmaker===\n* [https://www.youtube.com/playlist?list=PLywVcCl5U2n_7XRlxqZZmcewE4iu_LRLx VALOR Film Series]: Stories that honor our country's heroes and their accomplishments.\n*[https://www.youtube.com/playlist?list=PLywVcCl5U2n-j4vU0dIVoN43CITKWbIsh Legacy Films] (Made in partnership with the National Cemetery Administration): A series of short films on veterans buried in San Francisco and Golden Gate National Cemeteries\u2013 from stories of service in Civil War to Buffalo Soldier, from WWI to Vietnam to Iraq. \n* [https://www.imdb.com/title/tt9377262/?ref_=nv_sr_1 Noble Sissle's Syncopated Ragtime]: In this Academy Awards eligible documentary, Noble Sissle's incredible life spans \"The Harlem Hellfighters\" of World War I, Broadway Theatre, the Civil Rights movement, and decades of Black cultural production in this short, award-winning documentary.\n* [https://www.imdb.com/title/tt8777138/?ref_=nm_knf_t1 Guy Hircefeld, A Guy with a Camera]: In this Academy Awards eligible documentary, Guy Hircefeld, a veteran that served in the Israeli military at the start of its occupation of Palestine in the 1980s, now fights against Israeli occupation, ethnic cleansing, and environmental warfare. His only weapon is a camera.\n*  [https://www.imdb.com/title/tt9422390/?ref_=ttpl_pl_tt Nurse Helen Fairchild]: Bravery, Compassion and the will to save lives motivated the young Nurse Helen Fairchild to leave home in Pennsylvania and embark on a journey to Europe, where she served as a surgical nurse during the World War I.\n* [https://www.imdb.com/title/tt11540678/ Frank Maselskis: from WWII POW to Chosin Reservoir Survivor]: A prisoner of war in World War II, Frank Maselskis decides to join the Korean War, where he participates in the battle of Chosin, a brutal combat that took place in the most extreme weather conditions.\n* [https://www.imdb.com/title/tt11540612/ Alene B. Duerk: The First Woman Admiral]: Alene B. Duerk: The First Woman Admiral is a short documentary that tells the story of how Alene Duerk overcame gender stereotypes in the military to accomplish the highest rank ever achieved by a woman in the history of the US Navy.\n\n===As producer===\n* [http://www.eldoradofilms.net/profiles/ Women in Science]: Iliana Nossa (The Ionosphere) & Anne Virkki (Near Earth Asteroids), two female scientists at Arecibo Observatory, Puerto Rico.\n* [https://www.instagram.com/eldoradofilms_/ Cemetery Profiles and Field Notes]: In this series, we hope to tell the story of our National Cemeteries. Veteran Documentary Corps shot these films in late April 2019 as part of our partnership with the National Cemetery Administration. All films are available on our social media platforms.\n*[https://www.imdb.com/title/tt8231488/ Madame Mars] is an award-winning short film about women in space. As a new space age dawns, have women come far enough to go farther than they ever have before? Women have faced challenges while trying to study and explore Mars\u2013 from early space age pioneers to those currently working.\n*[https://objectorfilm.com/ Objector] directed by Molly Stuart tells the story of Atalya Ben Abba. Like all Israeli teenagers, Atalya Ben Abba is obligated to become a soldier. Unlike most, she questions the ethics of her country\u2019s military and becomes determined to challenge this rite of passage. Objector follows Atalya through her conscientious objection, imprisonment, and beyond, as she attempts to reconcile her Jewish identity, her love for her family and her homeland, and her dedication to Palestinian rights\n\n==Selected publications==\n*Bernardi, Daniel. ''The Birth of Whiteness:  Race and the Emergence of U.S. Cinema.''  1996.  Rutgers University Press.  {{ISBN|0-8135-2276-5}}\n*Bernardi, Daniel. ''Star Trek and History:  Race-ing Toward a White Future''.  1998. Rutgers University Press. {{ISBN|0-8135-2466-0}}\n*Bernardi, Daniel.  [http://flowtv.org/2005/04/cyborg-donna-haraway-race-pornography-hate-speech/ \"Where's the Beef?\"] ''Flow On-line'', Volume 2.  April 1, 2005.\n*[http://smallwarsjournal.com/jrnl/art/narrative-landmines \"Narrative Landmines: The Explosive Effects of Rumors in Syria and Insurgencies Around the World\"].  ''Small Wars Journal''.  March 21, 2013.\n* Word:ChristChurch, Autumn Season 2017. \"[https://www.audiomack.com/song/word-christchurch/james-gleick-time-travel James Gleick: Time Travel Feat. James Gleick, Dr Daniel Bernardi (interviewer)]\".  Audiomack.  July 19, 2017.\n*[http://startrekdom.blogspot.com/2007/06/prof-daniel-bernardi-on-star-trek-and.html \"Prof. Daniel Bernardi on Star Trek and Race.\"] (interview with Bernardi) ''Trekdom - Star Trek Fanzine''. June 25, 2007.\n*[http://www.federalnewsradio.com/1167/3539852/In-Depth-Show-Blog---January-10-2014 \"Lt. Cmdr. Daniel Bernardi.\"  ''In Depth Show''].  Federal News Radio.  January 10, 2014. Radio.\n\n==Sources quoting Bernardi==\n*[http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2011/09/08/scitech/main20103413.shtml \"Beam Me Up, Scotty\": 45 Years of Star Trek]. CBS News Tech Online.  September 8, 2011.\n*Di Rado, Alicia. \"[http://articles.latimes.com/1995-02-20/local/me-34149_1_star-trek Boldly Going to College: Fans of `Star Trek' TV series and movies have the chance to debate meaning and metaphor of cult hit's characters in campus clubs-and in the classroom].\"  ''Los Angeles Times''.  Feb 20, 1995.\n*Hayward, Susan.  ''Cinema Studies: The Key Concepts''.  Second Edition.  200. Routledge.\n*Johnson, Chloe.  [http://www.goldengatexpress.org/2014/10/13/fleet-week-2014/ \"Civilians Get A Taste of Naval Life At Annual Fleet Week\"].  ''Golden Gate XPress''. Oc