e Hodgson]]^\n*[[Haviland Routh]]^\n*[[Alex Kingan]]^\n*[[Alex Irving]]^\n*[[Arthur \"Toad\" Waud]]^\n*[[Aburey Mussen]] (Spare/did not play/on team picture)\n|non-players=\n* Harry Shaw (Manager/Secretary-Treasurer)\n* James Taylor (President of the Hockey Club) (missing from team picture)\n* ^Unknown who played Center, Rover, Right Wing and Left Wing, so the players are listed as forwards\n|engraving-notes=\n*  Montreal\n*-- 1894 --\n}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of pre-NHL seasons]]\n*[[List of Stanley Cup champions]]\n\n==References==\n*{{cite book | author=Coleman, Charles L. | title=The Trail of the Stanley Cup, Vol. 1, 1893\u20131926 inc. | pages=13\u201318}}\n* {{cite book |last=Podnieks |first=Andrew |author2=Hockey Hall of Fame |year=2004 |title=Lord Stanley's Cup |publisher=Triumph Books |pages=12, 50 |isbn=1-55168-261-3}}\n\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070323090826/http://www.collectionscanada.ca/hockey/024002-119.01-e.php description of first Stanley Cup final on ''Backcheck'']\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{succession box |\n  before = [[1893 AHAC season#Stanley Cup|Montreal HC<br>1893]] |\n  after = [[Montreal Victorias]]<br/>[[1895 AHAC Season|1895]] |\n  title = [[Montreal Hockey Club]]<br>[[List of Stanley Cup champions|Stanley Cup Champions]] |\n  years = 1894|\n}}\n{{succession box |\n  before = [[1893 AHAC season|1893]] |\n  after = [[1895 AHAC season|1895]] |\n  title = [[Amateur Hockey Association of Canada|AHAC seasons]] |\n  years = 1894|\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{Stanley Cup Finals}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:1894 Ahac Season}}\n[[Category:1893\u201394 in Canadian ice hockey|AHAC]]\n[[Category:Amateur Hockey Association of Canada seasons]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox sports season\n| title              = 1894 AHAC season\n| color              = \n| color text         = \n| league             = [[Amateur Hockey Association of Canada]]\n| sport              = [[ice hockey]]\n| logo               = \n| pixels             = \n| caption            = \n| duration           = January 5, 1894 \u2013 March 10, 1894\n| no_of_teams        = 5\n| attendance         = \n| TV                 = \n| draft              = \n| draft_link         = \n| top_pick           = \n| picked_by          = \n| season             = 1894\n| season_champs      = \n| season_champ_name  = \n| league_champs      = [[Montreal Hockey Club]]\n| league_champ_name  = Champion\n| second_place       = \n| minor_premiers     =\n| MVP                = \n| MVP_link           = \n| Cup_MVP            = \n| Cup_MVP_link       = \n| top_scorer         = \n| top_scorer_link    = \n| promote            = \n| promote_from       = \n| relegate           = \n| relegate_to        = \n| playoffs           = \n| playoffs_link      = \n| conf1              = \n| conf1_link         = \n| conf1_champ        = \n| conf1-runner-up    = \n| conf2              = \n| conf2_link         = \n| conf2_champ        = \n| conf2-runner-up    = \n| playoffs_MVP       = \n| playoffs_MVP_link  = \n| finals             = \n| finals_link        = \n| finals_champ       = \n| finals_runner-up   = \n| finals_MVP         = \n| finals_MVP_link    = \n| final_four_MVP     = \n| final_four_MVP_link= \n| seasonslist        = [[Amateur Hockey Association of Canada]]\n| seasonslistnames   = AHAC\n| prevseason_link    = [[1893 AHAC season]]\n| prevseason_year    = [[1893 AHAC season|1893]]\n| altseason_link    = \n| altseason_year    = \n| nextseason_link    = [[1895 AHAC season]]\n| nextseason_year    = [[1895 AHAC season|1895]]\n}}\n\nThe '''1894 [[Amateur Hockey Association of Canada]] season''' lasted from January 5 until March 10. Montreal HC would win the league and Canadian championship for the seventh season in a row.\n\n==Executive==\n{{Emergence of the NHL}}\n* President - W. Jack, Victorias\n* First Vice Pres. - A. Laurie, Quebec\n* Second Vice Pres. - [[Weldy Young|Weldy C. Young]], Ottawa\n* Secretary-Treasurer - J. A. Findlay, Montreal\n\n==Season==\n\n===Highlights===\nIn two games players scored five goals. In the opening game, in which Montreal soundly defeated Quebec 7\u20130, [[Haviland Routh]] scored five. On January 20, H. Russell of Ottawa scored five.\n\n===Final standing===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Team\n! Games Played\n! Wins\n! Losses\n! Ties\n! Goals For\n! Goals Against\n|-\n| [[Montreal Hockey Club]]\n| <center>8</center>\n| <center>5</center>\n| <center>3</center>\n| <center>0</center>\n| <center>25</center>\n| <center>15</center>\n|-\n| [[Ottawa Senators (original)|Ottawa Hockey Club]]\n| <center>8</center>\n| <center>5</center>\n| <center>3</center>\n| <center>0</center>\n| <center>24</center>\n| <center>16</center>\n|-\n| [[Montreal Victorias]]\n| <center>8</center>\n| <center>5</center>\n| <center>3</center>\n| <center>0</center>\n| <center>36</center>\n| <center>20</center>\n|-\n| [[Quebec Bulldogs|Quebec Hockey Club]]\n| <center>8</center>\n| <center>5</center>\n| <center>3</center>\n| <center>0</center>\n| <center>26</center>\n| <center>27</center>\n|-\n| [[Montreal Crystals]]\n| <center>8</center>\n| <center>0</center>\n| <center>8</center>\n| <center>0</center>\n| <center>10</center>\n| <center>43</center>\n|-\n|}\n\n==Playoffs==\nThe first Stanley Cup [[playoff]] game occurred on March 17, 1894. At the end of the 1894 AHAC season, four teams tied for the AHA championship with records of 5\u20133\u20130. This created problems for the AHA governors and the Cup's trustees since there was no tie-breaking system in place. After long negotiation and the withdrawal of Quebec from the championship situation, it was decided that a three-team tournament would take place in Montreal, with  Ottawa getting a bye to the finals (being the sole \"road\" team). The Montreal HC defeated the Montreal Victorias, 3 \u2013 2.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=PqwtAAAAIBAJ&sjid=AH4FAAAAIBAJ&hl=fr&pg=7331%2C1466196| title = Montrealers Victorious |newspaper= The Montreal Gazette |location= Montreal|date=1894-03-19|page=8}}</ref> Five days later on March 22, 1894, Montreal successfully defended their title with a 3 \u2013 1 win over Ottawa. The OHA champion [[Osgoode Hall]] challenged for the Cup, but this was abandoned due to the lack of natural ice.<ref>{{cite news |newspaper=Ottawa Citizen |date=March 10, 1911 |title=History of the Stanley Cup |page=5}}</ref>\n\n===Game one: Montreal Hockey Club vs. Montreal Victorias===\n\nIce conditions were described as not very good. The game was considered exciting, however, with Haviland Routh and Billy Barlow starring.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! width=\"120\" | Date\n! width=\"170\" | Winning Team\n! width=\"5\"   | Score\n! width=\"160\" | Losing Team\n! width=\"145\" | Location\n|-\n| March 17, 1894\n| [[Montreal Hockey Club]] || align=\"center\" | 3 \u2013 2 || [[Montreal Victorias]]\n| [[Victoria Skating Rink (Montreal)|Victoria Rink]]\n|}\n\n====Game one rosters====\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! Montreal HC\n! Goals\n! Pos.\n! Goals\n! Victorias\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left\" | Herbert Collins ||   || G  ||   ||style=\"text-align:left\" |  Gordon Lewis\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left\" | Allan Cameron   ||   || P  ||   ||style=\"text-align:left\" |   [[Mike Grant]]\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left\" | George James    ||   || CP ||   ||style=\"text-align:left\" |  William Pullan\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left\" | Billy Barlow    || 2 || F  || 1 ||style=\"text-align:left\" |  [[Shirley Davidson]]\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left\" | Clare Mussen    ||   || F  || 1 ||style=\"text-align:left\" |  [[Robert MacDougall]]\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left\" | Archie Hodgson  || 1 || F  ||   ||style=\"text-align:left\" |  Norman Rankin\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left\" | Haviland Routh  ||   || F  ||   ||style=\"text-align:left\" |  Reg Wallace\n|-\n| colspan=\"5\" | Referee: [[Weldy Young]], Ottawa\n|}\n\n===Game two: Ottawa Hockey Club vs. Montreal Hockey Club===\n\nThe final was close and in doubt until [[Billy Barlow]] scored the winning goal at 9'00\" of the third quarter.\n\nAccording to the ''Globe'' report of the game:\n\n:\"Team play was marred by the softness of the ice. Rough and foul play was frequent, both defences indulging freely in tripping and slashing. Young of Ottawa was injured by James in the second half and although he finished the game without apparent distress, fainted dead away at the end of it. After the match the victors were carried off the rink.\"<ref>{{Cite news |newspaper=The Globe |title=Montreallers Champions|date=March 23, 1894 |pages=6 |postscript=<!--None-->}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! width=\"120\" | Date\n! width=\"160\" | Winning Team\n! width=\"5\"   | Score\n! width=\"160\" | Losing Team\n! width=\"145\" | Location\n|-\n| March 22, 1894\n| [[Montreal Hockey Club]] || align=\"center\" | 3 \u2013 1 || [[Ottawa Senators (original)|Ottawa Hockey Club]]\n| [[Victoria Skating Rink (Montreal)|Victoria Rink]]\n|}\n\n==== Game two rosters ====\n{| class=\"wikitable\"  style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! Ottawa\n! Goals\n! Pos.\n! Goals\n! Montreal HC\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left\" | A. Morel           ||   || G  ||   || style=\"text-align:left\" | Herbert Collins\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left\" | [[Harvey Pulford]] ||   || P  ||   || style=\"text-align:left\" | Allan Cameron\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left\" | [[Weldy Young]]    ||   || CP ||   || style=\"text-align:left\" | George James\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left\" | [[Chauncy Kirby]] || 1 || F  ||   || style=\"text-align:left\" | Haviland Routh\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left\" | Herbert Russell    ||   || F  ||   || style=\"text-align:left\" | Clare Mussen\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left\" | Joe McDougall      ||   || F  || 2 || style=\"text-align:left\" | Archie Hodgson\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left\" | Sam McDougall      ||   || F  || 1 || style=\"text-align:left\" | Billy Barlow\n|-\n| colspan=\"5\" | Referee: Herbert Scott, Quebec\n|}\n\n==Schedule and results==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Month\n! Day\n! Visitor\n! Score\n! Home\n! Score\n|-\n|rowspan=10 valign=top| Jan.\n|| 5 || Quebec || 0 || '''Montreal''' || 7\n|-\n| 6 || Crystals || 1 || '''Ottawa''' || 6\n|-\n| 6 || Quebec || 3 || '''Victorias''' || 7\n|-\n| 13 || Victorias || 3 || '''Montreal'''|| 4 \n|-\n| 13 || Ottawa || 1 || '''Quebec''' || 4 \n|-\n| 18 || Crystals || 1 || '''Montreal''' || 3\n|-\n| 20 || Victorias || 1 || '''Ottawa'''|| 5\n|-\n| 20 || '''Quebec''' || 4 || Crystals || 1 \n|-\n| 27 || '''Ottawa''' || 4 || Montreal || 1\n|-\n| 27 || Crystals || 4 || '''Quebec''' || 8\n|-\n|rowspan=6 valign=top| Feb.\n|| 3 || '''Quebec''' || 3 || Montreal || 2\n|-\n| 9 || '''Ottawa''' || 3 || Crystals || 1\n|-\n| 10 || Montreal || 1 || '''Victorias''' || 2\n|-\n| 17 || Ottawa || 2 || '''Victorias''' || 3\n|-\n| 24 || '''Montreal''' || 5 || Ottawa || 1\n|-\n| 24 || Victorias || 3 || '''Quebec''' || 4\n|-\n|rowspan=4 valign=top| Mar.\n|| 2 || '''Montreal''' || 2 || Crystals || 1\n|-\n| 3 || Quebec || 0 || '''Ottawa''' || 2\n|-\n| 7 || Crystals || 0 || '''Victorias''' || 6\n|-\n| 10 || '''Victorias''' || 11 || Crystals  || 1\n|-\n|}\n\n==Player statistics==\n\n===Goaltending averages===\nNote: GP = Games played, GA = Goals against, SO = Shutouts, GAA = [[Goals against average]]\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Name\n! Club\n! GP\n! GA\n! SO\n! GAA\n|-\n| Collins, Herbert  ||Montreal  || 8 || 15 || 1 || 1.875\n|-\n| Morel, Albert         ||Ottawa    || 8 || 16 || 1 || 2.00\n|-\n| Lewis, Gordon     ||Victorias || 6 || 13 || 1 || 2.16\n|-\n| [[Robert Jones (Ice Hockey)|Jones, Robert]]     ||Victorias || 1 || 3  ||   || 3.00\n|-\n| Stocking, Frank   ||Quebec    || 8 || 27 ||   || 3.375\n|-\n| White,            ||Crystals  || 2 ||  8 ||   || 4.00\n|-\n| [[Hartland MacDougall|McDougall, Hartland]]     ||Victorias || 1 || 4  ||   || 4.00\n|-\n| Clapperton,       ||Crystals  || 4 || 18 ||   || 4.50\n|-\n| Carpenter,        ||Crystals  || 1 ||  6 ||   || 6.